  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+Bayesian-inference+Karl-Friston+information-theory+active-inference] IMPLEMENTATION-READY — Active Inference Engine (concrete code spec). Person = { beliefs: Record<string, number>, precision: Record<string, number>, priors: Record<string, number> }. predict(situation) = (1) compute prediction errors for each belief dimension (safety, status, autonomy, connection, competence), (2) weight each error by precision[dim], (3) if sum > threshold → update beliefs (learning), else → select action to reduce expected free energy. emotion = sign and magnitude of precision-weighted prediction error (positive surprise = joy, negative = fear/anger). behavior = gradient descent on expected free energy across possible actions. This maps every benchmark: grief = unresolvable prediction error on attachment model; bias = high-precision prior resisting update; depression = globally low precision (everything feels uncertain and uncontrollable). — Math: F = -log P(observations | model) + KL[Q(hidden states) || P(hidden states)]; minimize F by updating Q (perception) or acting to change observations; [dynamical-systems+catastrophe-theory+René-Thom+nonlinear-dynamics+bifurcation-theory] Catastrophe Theory Model of Behavioral Transitions. Humans don't change gradually — they snap. Model person as a dynamical system with stable attractors (equilibrium states: calm, angry, loving, dissociated). Situation = perturbation vector. Response = trajectory in state space. Key insight: René Thom's cusp catastrophe explains hysteresis — why getting someone angry requires less provocation than calming them down, why addiction has a snap-in threshold but gradual recovery. Person has two control parameters: arousal (ANS activation) and valence (approach/avoid). Behavior surface has fold: same stimulus → different response depending on history. Explains: emotional flooding, trauma triggers, falling in love, sudden insight (Aha = bifurcation), moral outrage cascades. Computable: state machine with attractor basins defined by (arousal, valence) coordinates. — Math: Cusp catastrophe: V(x) = x⁴ + ax² + bx; equilibria at dV/dx=0; fold surface creates sudden jumps; hysteresis emerges naturally from geometry; [information-theory+Kolmogorov-complexity+MDL+narrative-psychology+compression] Minimum Description Length (MDL) Narrative Compression Engine. The mind's job is not to predict the future — it's to compress experience into the shortest story that explains it. Identity = the current best-compressed narrative of the self. Cognitive biases = compression artifacts (like JPEG artifacts — lossy compression optimized for speed). Behavior = action that keeps the narrative valid without requiring re-compression. Predict: given situation, find action with minimum description length given current narrative. If action cost < rewrite cost → conform to old story. If situation is too incompressible → cognitive dissonance, anxiety, or narrative rupture (identity crisis). Explains: confirmation bias (compresses well into existing story), sunk cost (rewriting is expensive), denial (compression failure), therapy (guided narrative recompression). MDL is different from Bayesian: it penalizes model complexity explicitly, giving compactness as a first-class output alongside accuracy. — Math: MDL: best hypothesis H* = argmin[L(H) + L(data|H)]; description length L = -log₂P; identity coherence = 1/L(narrative); cognitive load = description length of current situation given narrative",
